It may be related to the Model 82A1®/M107®, but the M107A1 is far from a simple evolution. Driven by the demands of combat, every component was re-engineered to be lighter yet stronger. The result? A high-performance rifle that weighs five pounds less than the original M107, but is every bit as tough. Designed to be used with a suppressor, this one-of-a-kind rifle allows you to combine signature reduction capabilities with the flawless reliability of the original Barrett M107, but with a rifle weight reduction of 5 pounds. An all new bolt carrier group has been designed and is key to making the rifle suppressor-ready. Its steel four-port cylindrical muzzle brake is engineered to work seamlessly with a quick-attach Barrett QDL Suppressor. The lightweight aluminum upper receiver features an integrated 27 MOA optics rail. Inside the upper receiver, the bolt carrier rides on a hardened steel anti-wear strip for added durability. A thermal-guard cheek piece protects the user's face from extreme heat or cold. Advanced design and manufacturing make the M107A1 more precise than ever. The rear barrel stop and front barrel bushing are bolted and bonded with a high strength compound. A titanium barrel key and fully-chrome-lined bore and chamber add to the rifle's durability. Enhanced modularity is also a key feature of the M107A1. The rail-mounted aluminum rear grip can easily be reconfigured."

To see better photos visit the Eberlestock website:
The Eberlstock video does the best job explaining this pack and all the many features:

It has a unique articulating rear interior wall that allows a weapon to be carried near the wearer's back. When not carrying a weapon, the wall is pressed against the frame to maximize conventional interior load space. This pack also has a built-in rain cover that covers the entire pack.

Eberlestock F4M Terminator Pack is a high-capacity, versatile tactical backpack that's equally effective with or without a weapon. The Terminator can effortlessly bear all of your equipment like a cyborg, and there's an entire network of PALS webbing for the addition of extra pouches. This Eberlestock pack has been optimized with snipers and scouts in mind, and to that end the Eberlestock Terminator Front Loading Pack includes an innovative method of carrying any man-portable weapon, including high-powered sniper rifles with large rifle scopes.

While its sister pack, the Eberlestock G4 Operator, has an external scabbard, the Terminator allows you to carry your weapon in concealed fashion, on the interior. That's because the Eberlestock Terminator has an articulating rear interior wall that creates a hollow ""tunnel"" throughout the entire back of the pack. The tunnel is wide enough to fit any Eberlestock gun case or scabbard into the load case, where nothing but the tip of the scabbard peeks from the bottom of the pack. With rifles over 60"" long, the stock will stick out over the top pouch of the pack and can be covered with an Eberlestock Butt Cover. The orientation of the weapon slot allows you to carry your rifle closer to your back, improving the load distribution of the pack. When you're not carrying a weapon, the equipment in your pack will push the articulating wall back toward the frame, allowing you to make full use of all the Eberlestock Terminator Sniper Backpack's interior space.

Speaking of space, the Eberlestock F4 Terminator has enough pouches and additional storage potential to hold all your equipment, accessories, and weapons and still have room for more. The Terminator is a front-loading pack; the front door opens entirely, allowing you to organize the contents of your pack like you would a drawer. Tuck pouches line the interior of the pack, and transparent mesh pockets along the interior side walls allow you to see all your equipment at once. Eberlestock has even included a radio compartment in the back of the Eberlestock F4 Terminator Backpack. On the exterior, the Terminator has two large, two liter pouches on the front door, plus two long side pouches for tripods, spotting scopes, hydration systems, or other long and slender accessories.

The Eberlestock Terminator Full Format Pack also includes a fanny top pack which contains three storage compartments (one for a hydration system) and can compress the top load of your pack via the compression straps. The fanny top is removable and can be carried across your chest as a courier bag or around your waist as a fanny pack, allowing you to take a lightweight survival and first aid kit into areas where your pack can't or shouldn't go. If you need extra storage, you can easily attach Eberlestock pouches to virtually any part of the pack since it's riddled with PALS webbing. The two front door pouches, the side pouches, the fanny top pack, and even the weight belt are pouch-ready with multiple rows of Padlock webbing.""
Basic Pack Wt: 8 lb 12 oz (4.30 kg)

The SIX8™ weapons are short-stroke, gas-piston operated rifles chambered in the 6.8x43mm SPC cartridge. This cartridge was developed as part of the Enhanced Rifle Cartridge Program in which U.S. Special Operations soldiers, as well as armorers and other technicians from the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit, played a major role. Its primary purpose was to address the deficiencies in terminal performance seen with the 5.56x45mm NATO cartridge, while allowing the soldier to carry the same number of rounds with minimal weight penalty. It succeeds in doing so because it uses a heavier bullet with excellent accuracy, which delivers more energy across all effective ranges.

Until now, a major drawback of using the 6.8 cartridge in an M4 style weapon has been the lack of reliable magazines. So, when we designed the SIX8™ family of weapons, we started with the magazine. Partnering with Magpul®, the leader in polymer magazine engineering, we designed the first polymer 6.8 magazine. Building upon the magazine, we designed the SIX8™ platform for maximum reliability and improved ergonomics. The upper and lower receivers are designed to accommodate the slightly larger polymer magazine and to perfect the feed geometry for the 6.8 cartridge. In addition, we have prompted Federal Ammunition to develop new lines of affordably priced, high performance 6.8 ammunition for commercial, law enforcement and military applications.

As with the IC family, the weapons in the new SIX8™ family are fully ambidextrous and equally suited to right- or left-handed operators. The SIX8™ rifles are based on the familiar Stoner M4/AR15/M16 architecture, but they have been optimized specifically for use with the 6.8 cartridge.
The new SIX8™ family combines the ultimate in ergonomic user-friendly rifles with the outstanding mid-range 6.8 cartridge.

531,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2158531,For Sale:  URGENT! Gaston County Sheriff Patrol Car break in,"Gaston County, Charlotte, North Carolina",FREE,"Listed On: Thursday, October 3, 2013",Handguns,no type,no type,no type,Pistol,"List of items to watch for below along with link to the actual story.

Someone stole a county-issued gun, Taser, Sheriff’s Office badges and other equipment from an officer’s parked car, a deputy reported Monday night. The Gaston County Sheriff’s deputy’s car was parked at Ultimate Fitness on Westover Street in Lowell.  Deputy Crystal Barnes was off duty and working out from 6:30 p.m. until 8 p.m., according to a report from the Lowell Police Department. When she returned to her 2012 Jeep Compass, she noticed her work bag, gym bag and purse were all missing.

Thieves also took her daughter’s book bag. Police believe the vehicle was locked and someone forced their way into the Jeep. Lowell Police are heading up the investigation, but Gaston County Sheriff Alan Cloninger said the Sheriff’s Office is helping.

“We’re doing everything we can to assist Lowell in recovering the items and catching whoever is responsible,” Cloninger said. The first step is sending out a BOLO, or “be on the lookout” alert for the items, which also include a uniform, bullet-proof vest and a now-deactivated courthouse security card.

Those alerts usually go to law enforcement agencies within 100 miles, but Cloninger said local authorities will ask officers across the state to keep an eye out for the stolen county property. It’s important to get the items back where they belong, police said. “Getting them off the street is very important with the Taser and the other weapons, even the ballistic vest,” said Lowell Police Chief Mark Buchanan. “It’s stuff that we definitely don’t want in the wrong hands.”

With recognizable marks such as the Gaston County Sheriff’s logo and Sheriff’s Office star, the items should be easily spotted if the thieves try to sell them, Buchanan said. The deputy’s car was the only one broken into in the parking lot, Buchanan said. But Cloninger doesn’t believe the off-duty officer was targeted. “Anybody can be a victim of crime, including law enforcement officers,” he said.
Police reports say officers will review recordings of video surveillance outside the gym. The owner of the gym said there’s never been a problem with car break-ins before.

Thieves made away with: A Gaston County Sheriff’s uniform, bulletproof vest ,Glock Model 22 – 40 caliber with a Gaston County Sheriff’s deputy logo and star, a Taser, two Gaston County silver deputy badges, three magazines for the glock 22, pepper spray and holster, six belt keepers, Sam Brown duty belt basket weave, Gould and riches holster, double magazine pouch, police radio, Gaston County Sheriff’s Office silver collar pins, silver name plate with C. Barnes written on it, Gaston County Sheriff’s I.D.’s, Gaston County courthouse security card and large key ring.
